> The fix tries to ignore the closure of outer lambdas ...

Does this mean, the outer lambda will not be present in the AST?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > The fix tries to ignore the closure of outer lambdas ...
> 
> Does this mean, the outer lambda will not be present in the AST?
> To prove that all is fine, you might want to create a test case where completion needs type information from an argument of the outer lambda 😊 - which would be very cool if it worked!

This appears to be an awesome fix. Saying "appears" just because I'm not able to 100% explain why it works. I did observe that the effect is by pushing the automaton into more parsing after detecting an error, and only this parsing will eventually trigger attachOrphanCompletionNode() which is necessary to build the RecoveredBlock containing all the lambda magic.

I'll mention this to Srikanth when I speak to him next time, maybe he can enlighten me more about the concept of committing a snapshot 😊

The existing breakpoints from the UI are never send to gdb, because the old code never call attachDebuggerToProcess. The method attachDebuggerToProcess contains the step connecting the process breakpoints to the debugger (GDBProcess_7_2).
In remote the attach is already done. The condition in the old code suppose that no attach is done. I remove condition excluding the remote session to be attach to the debugger and I modify conditions supposing that no attach are made. The attach to process is not called in case of remote session.

I think there might be a few misunderstandings here.

To my knowledge, (I can obviously be wrong here and if so, please correct me!) a remote session always involve a gdb server. It can be running on the same computer as the GDB client or on a different one that is accessible over network, serial or some other connection.
Attach to a already running process is something that is always done locally and can never happen over a network unless you also involve a GDB server, but then you are back to a "normal" remote session.


So, based on the above, I'm not sure when it's ever relevant to do the attach to process for a remote session.
@John, am I missing something here or is my understanding in-line with what the meaning of LOCAL and REMOTE in the code?

Patch Set 6:

Hello Jonathan,

Before you spend more time on this gerrit, can you please explain why this is needed?
I've been reading your comments several times so far and I'm still not sure in what situation it's needed.

To my understanding, we have the following use-cases in CDT:
1. Launch the application though the GDB client -> local session
2. Attach to an already running application on the same computer -> local attach session
3. Connect to a GDB server (can be both on the same computer and on another) -> remote session

Is there any other use-case that you think of?
If not, in what of the above use-cases is the breakpoints not applied to the GDB client?

To conclude, a small reproducible scenario would greatly help to understand what issue you are attempting to resolve.

Patch Set 6:

> To my knowledge, (I can obviously be wrong here and if so, please correct me!) a remote session always involve a gdb server. It can be running on the same computer as the GDB client or on a different one that is accessible over network, serial or some other connection.
> Attach to a already running process is something that is always done locally and can never happen over a network unless you also involve a GDB server, but then you are back to a "normal" remote session.
> 
> So, based on the above, I'm not sure when it's ever relevant to do the attach to process for a remote session.

> @John, am I missing something here or is my understanding in-line with what the meaning of LOCAL and REMOTE in the code?

@Torbjörn, the RemoteGdbLaunchDelegate allows the user to create a gdbserver process and then connect to it via RSP in the FinalLaunchSequence. This is distinct from the GdbAttachLaunchDelegate which can be configured to assume the presence of an existing gdbserver process and connect to it in the FinalLaunchSequence. This patch addresses the case of an attach session to an existing gdbserver process. This will be of SessionType.REMOTE to indicate connection via RSP.

messages.message: Patch Set 2: Commit message was updated.

Patch Set 4:

I am not familiar with this topic. however this looks like a O(n^2) loop. Shouldn't it be a "merge-join"? i.e. would be faster to have both lists sorted O(n log(n)) before merging them - in only one direction?

Patch Set 4:

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> I am not familiar with this topic. however this looks like a O(n^2) loop. Shouldn't it be a "merge-join"? i.e. would be faster to have both lists sorted O(n log(n)) before merging them - in only one direction?

Yes, that algorithm can be O(m*n*log(n)) in the worst-case. I used 
- m-> element count to be added 
- n -> tree size. 

As an explanation, lets have a look at two scenarios:
- Worst case: The tree contains only elements for which 'comparator.compare(o0, o1)==0 && !o1.equals(o2)' is true:
  - iterates over the elements to insert -> m
  - calculates the index for insertion (binary search) -> log n  
  - walks forwards and backwards from the insertionIndex to search for potential duplicates (the while loop). As all elements compare to each other with '0', all elements are visited -> n

-> The algorithm is =(m*n*log(n)) in the worst case


- Best case: The tree contains only elements for which 'comparator.compare(o0, o1)!=0' is true:
  - iterates over the elements to insert -> m
  - calculates the index for insertion (binary search) -> log n  
  - walks forwards and backwards from the insertionIndex to search for potential duplicates. The while loop does only two steps in all cases, as all elements compare to each other with '1' or '-1". -> No effect for the O() calculation.

-> The algorithm is O(m log n) in the best (and the more realistic) case.

Both lists are already sorted at this point, but I do not see how this helps to to build the add algorithm in O(n log n) as we we need a duplication detection (only possible in O(n) for the worst case) and the insertion itself is already implemented in O(m log n).

Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)

> Yes, that algorithm can be O(m*n*log(n)) in the worst-case. I used 

ok, i understood that now. thanks for explaining. 
I wonder why AbstractTreeViewer.add() does not describe that equal Elements are not inserted but updated. Also is see in the javadoc of AbstractTreeViewer: "As of 3.2, AbstractTreeViewer supports multiple equal elements" which contradicts skipping equal elements. I don't know what is supposed to happen but the javadoc seems to be wrong at some place

Patch Set 4:

> Patch Set 4:
> I wonder why AbstractTreeViewer.add() does not describe that equal Elements are not inserted but updated. 
That's a good point. I think the javadoc of the AbstractTreeViewer.add()/AbstractTreeViewer.createAddedElements() should mention that 'refresh only' behaviour.

> Also is see in the javadoc of AbstractTreeViewer: "As of 3.2, AbstractTreeViewer supports multiple equal elements" which contradicts skipping equal elements. I don't know what is supposed to happen but the javadoc seems to be wrong at some place
This is only a contradiction at first glance: The java doc describes that the AbstractTreeViewer supports multiple equal elements with !different! parent chains. There is no contradiction to the duplicate detection in this code, as the duplicates are only searched within the items[] containing all Items with the same parent:
 Item[] items = getChildren(widget);

items[] does not contain all objects shown in the whole tree.
